    12	
    13	# Documentation Authoring Hub (sk-doc)
    14	
    15	One advisor identity, eleven workflow packets, one shared create-quality-control backbone. `sk-doc` is the parent hub for documentation and OpenCode-component authoring. It holds NO per-packet logic: it routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`, and each packet keeps its own contract in its nested folder. The cross-cutting create-quality-control pipeline (validators, global standards, frontmatter/llms/template assets) lives once in `shared/` and is consumed by every packet.
    16	
    17	---
    18	
    19	## 1. WHEN TO USE
    20	
    21	Use this skill for documentation and OpenCode-component authoring, and for document-quality work. The hub classifies the request, resolves a `workflowMode`, and loads the matching nested packet.
    22	
    23	| Mode | Use it for | Packet | Command |
    24	|------|------------|--------|---------|
    25	| **create-skill** | Scaffold an OpenCode skill (and, via `create-skill-parent`, a parent hub with nested mode packets) | `create-skill/` | `/create:skill`, `/create:skill-parent` |
    26	| **create-readme** | Author a folder README or an install guide (install-guide is a folded variant) | `create-readme/` | `/create:readme` |
    27	| **create-agent** | Scaffold an OpenCode agent (permission/authority frontmatter) | `create-agent/` | `/create:agent` |
    28	| **create-command** | Scaffold an OpenCode slash command (argument-hint + allowed-tools + router/presentation split) | `create-command/` | `/create:command` |
    29	| **create-feature-catalog** | Author a feature-catalog inventory package | `create-feature-catalog/` | `/create:feature-catalog` |
    30	| **create-manual-testing-playbook** | Author a manual-testing-playbook package | `create-manual-testing-playbook/` | `/create:manual-testing-playbook` |
    31	| **create-benchmark** | Author MCP-promotion, behavior, conformance, skill-benchmark, and model-benchmark packages or inputs | `create-benchmark/` | `/create:benchmark` |
    32	| **create-flowchart** | Generate and validate an ASCII flowchart | `create-flowchart/` | `/create:flowchart` |
    33	| **create-changelog** | Author a global or packet-local changelog entry (version bump + topology-aware placement) | `create-changelog/` | `/create:changelog` |
    34	| **create-diff** | Produce a local, Git-free before/after review of an edited document (text/Markdown/HTML/DOCX/text-PDF) as a self-contained HTML report | `create-diff/` | — (routes via aliases) |
    35	| **create-quality-control** | Validate / score / optimize an EXISTING document (extract → DQI → HVR → validate) | `create-quality-control/` | `/doc:quality` |
    36	
    37	### When NOT to Use
    38	- Code implementation, tests, or debugging — use `sk-code`.
    39	- Git worktree, branch, commit, PR, or release work — use `sk-git`.
    40	- Spec-folder workflow / memory / save context — use `system-spec-kit`.
    41	- Design judgment, visual direction, motion, or UI audit — use `sk-design`.
    42	- The `shared/` backbone is consumed by the packets, not invoked as a user workflow.
    43	
    44	---
    45	
    46	## 2. SMART ROUTING
    47	
    48	Routing is **registry-driven at runtime and packet-authored at source**. Each nested packet's single `Keyword triggers:` line is the source of truth for its routing vocabulary; `mode-registry.json` and `hub-router.json` are synchronized projections that the hub reads without re-deriving mappings during a request. The advisor routes any documentation/authoring query to the single identity `sk-doc`; the hub then picks the packet.
    49	
    50	> **Compiled routing (opt-in, flag-gated, additive).** When `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1`, resolve the mode via the compiled router contract first:
    51	> ```bash
    52	> node .opencode/bin/compiled-route.cjs --hub sk-doc --prompt "<task>"
    53	> ```
    54	> Follow the returned decision — `route` (use its `targets`), `clarify`/`defer` (disambiguate), `reject` (refuse). On a `{"servingAuthority":"legacy"}` sentinel or any error, use the routing below. The front door self-gates on serving-authority, and the flag is **off by default**, so this is inert until compiled routing is activated for `sk-doc`.
    55	
    56	### The discriminator
    57	- **`workflowMode`** — the public packet key (e.g. `create-skill`, `create-quality-control`). `create-skill-parent` is a second mode over the same `create-skill` packet.
    58	- **`packetKind`** — `workflow` for every sk-doc packet (there is no surface axis; the create-quality-control pipeline is universal doctrine in `shared/`, not orthogonal stack-evidence).
    59	- **`backendKind`** — `template-scaffold` for the create-* generators, `create-quality-control` for the create-quality-control mode.
    60	
    61	### Routing rule
    62	```
    63	SKILL_ROOT = path containing this SKILL.md
    64	REGISTRY = SKILL_ROOT / "mode-registry.json"
    65	HUB_ROUTER = SKILL_ROOT / "hub-router.json"
    66	
    67	def _guard_in_skill(relative_path):
    68	  resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()
    69	  resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)
    70	  if resolved.suffix.lower() not in {".md", ".json"}:
    71	    raise ValueError("only skill-local markdown/json router resources are routable")
    72	  return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()
    73	
    74	def load_if_available(relative_path, seen):
    75	  guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)
    76	  if guarded not in seen and (SKILL_ROOT / guarded).exists():
    77	    load(guarded)
    78	    seen.add(guarded)
    79	    return True
    80	  return False
    81	
    82	seen = set()
    83	if not REGISTRY.exists() or not HUB_ROUTER.exists():
    84	  return defer("router metadata missing; inspect sk-doc/mode-registry.json and sk-doc/hub-router.json")
    85	
    86	read mode-registry.json and hub-router.json
    87	classify the request to one or more workflowMode values using hub-router.json
    88	  (dominant authoring/quality intent; a command like /create:agent resolves directly)
    89	
    90	if confidence is low, intent is contradictory, or routerPolicy.defaultMode is null and no mode wins:
    91	  load_if_available("shared/references/quick-reference.md", seen)
    92	  return UNKNOWN_FALLBACK with a checklist to confirm workflowMode, target document/component, inputs, and validation expectations
    93	
    94	for each resolved workflowMode:
    95	  entry = the matching mode-registry.json modes[] item
    96	  if entry is missing or entry.packetKind != "workflow":
    97	    return defer("unknown sk-doc workflowMode; extend mode-registry.json and create a packet first")
    98	  if not load_if_available(f"{entry.packet}/SKILL.md", seen):
    99	    return defer("registered packet SKILL.md is missing; repair the packet before routing")
   100	
   101	return single or orderedBundle according to hub-router.json routerPolicy.outcomes
   102	```
   103	`routerPolicy.defaultMode` is `null`: an unclear documentation intent asks for disambiguation rather than forcing a stale default. `hub-router.json` carries the router signals, vocabulary classes, default fallback resource, and bundle rules. Outcomes are `single`, `orderedBundle`, or `defer` — there is no `surfaceBundle` (no surface axis).
   104	
   105	Per-packet behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own authoring contract, references, assets, scripts, and templates.
   106	
   107	This hub does **not** use keyed resource discovery (`references/<key>/` or `assets/<key>/`) at the hub root: there are no hub-root `references/` or `assets/` directories, and packet resources stay inside their owning packet or the shared backbone. If a future workflow needs keyed resource subdirectories, add that behavior inside the owning packet using guarded runtime discovery; do not hardcode resource inventories in this hub.
   108	
   109	---
   110	
   111	## 3. HOW IT WORKS
   112	
   113	### Layout
   114	```
   115	sk-doc/
   116	  SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-packet logic)
   117	  mode-registry.json     # the eleven-packet discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)
   118	  hub-router.json        # router signals + vocabulary classes
   119	  description.json       # hub advisor descriptor
   120	  graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill
   121	  changelog/  manual-testing-playbook/  benchmark/
   122	  create-skill/  create-readme/  create-agent/  create-command/
   123	  create-feature-catalog/  create-manual-testing-playbook/
   124	  create-benchmark/  create-flowchart/  create-changelog/  create-diff/  create-quality-control/    # nested workflow packets
   125	  scripts/               # facade symlinks -> shared/ + owning packets (tool paths only)
   126	  shared/                # create-quality-control backbone: validators, global standards, shared assets
   127	```
   128	
   129	Each packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `README.md`, `changelog/`, and moved `references/`/`assets/`/`scripts/`) and carries **no** `graph-metadata.json`, so the advisor discovers exactly one `sk-doc` identity.
   130	
   131	### Shared backbone
   132	`shared/` holds the universal create-quality-control pipeline consumed by every packet: generic validator scripts (`shared/scripts/`), cross-cutting standards and vocabulary (`shared/references/`), and shared templates (`shared/assets/`). The `sk-doc/scripts/` root directory keeps facade symlinks pointing inward to `shared/` and the owning packets so tool paths resolve. There are no hub-root `assets/` or `references/` aggregation directories: consumers reference each packet's own `assets/`/`references/` or the `shared/` backbone directly.
   133	
   134	---
   135	
   136	## 4. RULES
   137	
   138	### ✅ ALWAYS
   139	- **ALWAYS** resolve a packet through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.
   140	- **ALWAYS** keep authoring contracts in the packets; the hub stays routing-only.
   141	- **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one identity.
   142	- **ALWAYS** keep the create-quality-control pipeline as one shared source under `shared/`, consumed by the packets.
   143	- **ALWAYS** keep changelogs as real files at the hub and in each packet — never symlinked.
   144	
   145	### ⛔ NEVER
   146	- **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` inside a packet or `shared/`.
   147	- **NEVER** put per-packet authoring logic in the hub.
   148	- **NEVER** add a surface axis or a `surfaceBundle` outcome — sk-doc is workflow-only.
   149	
   150	### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF
   151	- A new documentation workflow is needed — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.
   152	- A packet would become a near-empty shell (generic doctrine, no type-specific behavior) — fold it into `shared/` instead.
   153	
   154	---
   155	
   156	## 5. REFERENCES
   157	
   158	- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (eleven packets; `packetKind: workflow`).
   159	- Hub router: `hub-router.json` (signals + vocabulary classes).
   160	- Advisor descriptor: `description.json`; skill-graph identity: `graph-metadata.json`.
   161	- Packets: `create-skill/`, `create-readme/`, `create-agent/`, `create-command/`, `create-feature-catalog/`, `create-manual-testing-playbook/`, `create-benchmark/`, `create-flowchart/`, `create-changelog/`, `create-diff/`, `create-quality-control/`.
   162	- Shared backbone: `shared/scripts/`, `shared/references/`, `shared/assets/`.
   163	- Parent-skill pattern: `create-skill/references/parent-skill/parent-skills-nested-packets.md`.
